4. What Prior Art 2 actually teaches

US 2019/0339860 A1 is mainly about context-specific watch user interfaces, especially watch-face graphical objects/complications that move among a sequence of predefined locations on a watch display. The reference describes a watch UI with a first graphical object at a first location and a second graphical object at a last location, then, in response to user input, the first and second graphical objects are moved or redisplayed at different sequence locations. 

The reference also teaches that the graphical objects can be complications corresponding to applications, and that some complications display data from their respective applications. It defines complications as watch-face features that can provide data obtained from applications and can launch a corresponding application when selected. 

Most importantly for the examiner’s objection, Prior Art 2 teaches that when complications move between locations, their size and amount of displayed information may change. For example, a weather complication may include additional weather information in one location, while a heart-rate complication may include additional low/high heart-rate information in a larger location. 

